According to the wikipedia page about curl curl can be defined implicily as $$(
abla 	imes 	extbf{F} ) \scriptsize{ ullet} 
ormalsize{\hat{n}} = \lim_{A ightarrow 0}  rac{1}{|A|} \oint_C 	extbf{F} \scriptsize{ ullet} 
ormalsize{	extbf{dr}}$$ My question is, specifically, is this definition limited to only two dimensions? If not, how would I apply it to higher dimensions? For example, if I had a vector field defined by $	extbf{F}(x,y)=<x^2-y,y^2+x>$ the line integral at (a,b) could be defined by $$x-a=r \cos(t) \wedge y-b=r \sin(t)$$ $$ rac{dx}{dt}=-r\sin(t) \wedge  rac{dy}{dt}=r\cos(t)$$ $$\oint_C 	extbf{F} \scriptsize  ullet 
ormalsize 	extbf{dr} \= \int_0^{2\pi} \large [ 
ormalsize (r \ \cos(t)+a)^2-(r \ \sin(t)+b) \large] 
ormalsize  rac{dx}{dt} dt + \int_0^{2\pi} \large [ 
ormalsize (r \ \sin(t) + b)^2+(r \cos(t) + a ) \large ] 
ormalsize  rac{dy}{dt} dt\= 2 \pi r^2$$ and $A = \pi r^2$ so $ rac{1}{A}= rac{1}{\pi r^2}$ which makes $$\lim_{A ightarrow 0}  rac{1}{A} \oint_C 	extbf{F} \scriptsize{ ullet} 
ormalsize{	extbf{dr}} = \lim_{r ightarrow 0}  rac{2 \pi r^2}{\pi r^2} =\lim_{r ightarrow 0} 2 = 2 $$ Since $\hat{n}$ for the $xy$-plane is simply $<0,0,1>$ and since the curl would also be pointing in the same direction, then the curl, expressed as a vector in 3-space must be $<0,0,2>$. On WolframAlpha, entering curl [x^2-y,y^2+x,0] gives us the exact same answer. That was a little involved, to be honest, but I feel it was necessary for this question. A follow up question I have to ask is, if I were to apply this specifically to three dimensions, would a simple line integral in 3-space provide a sufficient answer, or would it need a surface integral?

